This paper focuses on the task of generating long structured sentences with explicit discourse markers, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a novel model architecture, which involves interpreting relations between two discourses in the embedding space, indicating the use of machine learning techniques. This suggests that cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) are also likely sub-categories. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of automatic evaluations, which could involve metrics such as accuracy or perplexity, indicating the use of statistical methods, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper may involve the use of image data, as the datasets can be accessed by a URL, suggesting that cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is a less likely but still possible sub-category.
